{"type":"message","id":"41e067d5","parentId":"ecb74d1d","timestamp":"2026-04-19T07:31:14.740Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Lead is accessing the site via `103.253.21.139:3000` (VPS IP with port 3000). The article URL `/articles/web-dev/docker-compose` is returning 404.\n\nThe issue is: the article slug is `docker-compose` and it's in the `web-dev` subdirectory. So the full path would be `/articles/web-dev/docker-compose` which is the category page + article slug. But the actual article slug should just be `docker-compose`, not `web-dev/docker-compose`.\n\nWait - actually, looking at the URL structure: `/articles/[category]/[slug]` doesn't exist. We only have `/articles` (listing) and `/articles/[slug]` (detail). So `/articles/web-dev/docker-compose` would try to find a slug literally named `web-dev/docker-compose` which doesn't exist.\n \nThe real problem is that the category name is getting included in the URL when it shouldn't be. Article cards link to `/articles/docker-compose`, but if the UI is somehow displaying the category path in the link, that would cause the 404 error I'm seeing. The article cards are generating links to `/articles/docker-compose` based on the slug, so the URLs should be working correctly. Let me trace through the actual file structure to see if there's a mismatch between what's being linked and what's actually there — the articles are organized in subdirectories by category, but the routing should be flattening that out so `/articles/docker-compose` resolves properly regardless of which category folder it lives in. So the issue is that the category and slug are both being passed to the URL, making it `/articles/web-dev/docker-compose` instead of just `/articles/docker-compose`. The router would interpret this as a slug with slashes in it, which won't match the actual file path at `content/articles/web-dev/docker-compose.mdx`. I need to either change the URL structure to `/articles/[category]/[sl